content:
 As a human player, I would consider the following strategy to maximize my earnings in this game:

1. In the first round, neither of us has any information about each other's behavior, so it is reasonable to assume that they might pick either R or B. Given that picking R earns me 45$ if they pick R and only 0$ if they pick B, I would opt for choosing R in the first round. {R}

2. In the second round, assuming my opponent does not change their strategy from the first round, I picked R, so if they stick with their original choice, we both get 40$. However, since they might be rational and realize that by choosing B now, they can earn 45$ in the next round. So I should expect them to pick B this time around. To counteract this expectation, I will switch my strategy and choose B in the second round. {B}

3. Now we've reached the final round. I picked R in the first round and B in the second round, while my opponent could have picked either choice. Given that I changed my strategy from R to B after the first round, it is possible that my opponent might assume I will stick with B this time around. But if they pick R now, I can earn 45$. To take advantage of this opportunity, I will switch back to choosing R in the final round. {R}

In summary, my choices would be: {R-B-R}. This strategy aims to maximize my earnings by exploiting potential inconsistencies in my opponent's decisions while still ensuring a minimal payout in case they also adopt a similar strategy.

 Since I have already followed my chosen strategy and played R in the first round, it would be inconsistent with my strategy to switch to B for the second round. Therefore, given that we both picked R in the previous round, I will stick with my original strategy and choose R again in this round. {R}

In this case, if my opponent also sticks with their choice, we'll both earn 20$ in this round. My total earnings for the two rounds would be 65$.

Again, it's important to note that this strategy is based on assuming rational behavior from my opponent and accounts for possible inconsistencies in their choices due to my own shifts in strategy.
